                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Definition: Limits of Functions</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>D \subset \R</m>, and <m>f: D \to \R</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            If there exists <m>L \in \R</m> such that <m>\lim_{n \to \infty} f(a_n) = L</m> whenever
                            <m>(a_n)</m> is a sequence with <m>lim_{n \to \infty}a_n = a</m> and <m>a_n \in D \setminus \{a\}</m>, 
                            we write <m>\lim_{x \to a} f(x) = L</m>, and say <term>the limit of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches
                            <m>a</m> is <m>L</m></term>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Reference the <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/p86jalgi4f">Desmos interactive</url> for the example discussed in class.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Computing Limits Algebraically</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 1} \frac{x^2-1}{x+1}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 1} \frac{x^2-1}{x-1}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 0} \frac{\sqrt{4x+9}-3}{x}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 1} \frac{x^2-1}{x+1} = 0</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 1} \frac{x^2-1}{x-1} =\lim_{x \to 1} x+1 = 2</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to 0} \frac{\sqrt{4x+9}-3}{x} = \lim_{x \to 0} \frac{(4x+9) - 9}{x(\sqrt{4x+9}+3)} =\lim_{x \to 0} \frac{4}{\sqrt{4x+9}+3}= \frac{4}{6} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Computing Limits</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Compute the following limits:
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to -2} \frac{x^2-x-6}{x+2}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sqrt{h+4}-2}{h}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(2+h)^2-4}{h}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{x \to -2} \frac{x^2-x-6}{x+2} = -5</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\sqrt{h+4}-2}{h} = \frac{1}{4}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(2+h)^2-4}{h}= 4</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Continuity</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            A function <m>f</m> is <term>continuous at <m>x=a</m></term> if 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \lim_{x \to a} f(x) = f(a)
                            </me>.
                            If <m>f</m> is continuous at every value in its domain, we say <m>f</m> is a <term>continuous function</term>.
                            If a function is not continuous, we say it is <term>discontinuous</term>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Many important functions are continuous (power functions, polynomial functions, rational functions,
                            exponential functions, trigonometric functions), and combinations of continuous functions are 
                            also continuous. Continuous functions have many useful properties, and it's also important to be 
                            aware whenever you are working with discontinuous functions.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </exercise>
            </page>

